"Yes, boss. They must be on their way now; we gave them time to get provisions at the mess." At exactly 5:00, Company Exodus gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a box and started speaking.
"We are deploying to FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We must support the ongoing siege and the planned attack on Ianlos to put down the insurgency. From there, we will have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Assemble your units and board the vehicles."
The company dispersed, with each member joining their respective units, and the sergeants helped them board the tanks. Cohren climbed into one of the armored vehicles, at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he knew little about them. Sitting on the side, with his legs hanging down, he adjusted his pack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat mic.
"Hey Cohren, did Harris still have Snowball?" asked Nemic as they settled in.
"You mean the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning when they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure of it."
Cohren glanced at one of the tanks and saw Harris with his unit. From the back of his pack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken bobbing its head to observe its surroundings.
"Yeah, he's always had it," replied Cohren as the tank turret opened with a click to let his commander pass through.
"All the tanks were on the move," declared the commander calmly but clearly, wearing his helmet. The engines of a tank platoon and Stryker vehicles roared as they began to advance. When Cohren's vehicle, the Kronos, had its brakes released and started moving to form up, it jolted. The tanks deployed in a V formation to cross the plains of Itania. Winter storms had frozen the marshes and forests, but the mud was still there.
After about an hour, one of the new recruits, named Orson in Cohren's memory, spoke up. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, haven't you?"
"Yeah, Operation Firestorm," replied Cohren. "We thought we'd wrap it up in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimating is a weak word," said Nemic as he joined the conversation. "They had more weapons and men than we anticipated. They managed to bring down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Shit, we should see them from where we are."
"Well, I'll hold strong for the Federation," said Orson with a hint of provocation. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You say that now, but from experience, I know that new 18-year-old recruits like you take cover as soon as you hear gunfire," declared Craith.
"I think we'll be soon finding out," said Cohren laughing. Orson did not continue the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We detect thermal signatures about 300 meters, 20 degrees right."
Cohren climbed to the top of the tank and put on his optical glasses. By activating thermal vision, he could see distant thermal signatures.
"Yeah, I see them," replied Cohren through his throat mic.
"Enemies?" asked another recruit, Natayla.
"Can't say for sure," declared Cohren. He activated his mic and said: "Company Exodus, don't shoot unless they shoot at you, let them come out."
As they approached, the small thermal signatures went from blurry spots to more distinct shapes. As they got closer, one of them ran toward something, picked it up, then dashed back to the small ridge where they were. The silhouettes took up shooting positions.
"We have contacts," shouted Shaw into the radio, as orange tracers were fired from the crest. Bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, while soldiers jumped from vehicles to take cover behind them. A anti-tank missile whistled past and exploded behind the formation, sending debris onto one of the vehicles. Another missile hit the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew emerged and dove for cover as the ammunition burned.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 275 meters. 'Fire,' " yelled the tank platoon commander over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells flying towards the crest and exploding, sending mud and rocks into the air.
"Send the Sentinels," cried Knoxx, who was observing the crest through his binoculars. The rear of one of the Cerberuses opened up, and an unarmed soldier wearing a special helmet emerged. He shouted orders into a square microphone, and two Sentinels, or Sentinelles as they were officially named, rushed outside. Their thin metal limbs swung forward as they sprinted. They were armed, but their weapons were attached to their backs.
"Do we kill them or capture them?" asked Craith as they watched.
"It seems we'll be capturing them," said Cohren as the two Sentinelles disappeared in a cloud of ash and smoke. Cries and gunfire echoed from the crest but stopped quickly. A moment later, the two Sentinelles returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots dragged on the ground. Once safe within the platoon, they dropped the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he collapsed in the mud and snow.
Shaw walked towards the individual, who was beginning to rise. He turned towards one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," replied the Sentinel. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned towards Cohren and Craith, who stood beside him. "Both of you, would you kindly dispose of this man for us?"
